  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Performing background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training employees on identification and prevention\n\n4. Record keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer information\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\n5. Risk assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers and transactions\n- Implementing enhanced due diligence\n- Monitoring international transactions\n\n6. Legal penalties\n- Potential significant fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced through regulations like the Bank Secrecy Act and international standards set by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).\n\nFinancial institutions must proactively implement comprehensive strategies to detect and prevent money laundering activities.",
